<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1906-11-06T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1906-11-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="411" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d411">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 2160.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">British Ambassador</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">British
                                        Embassy</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1906-11-06"><hi rend="italic">November 6,
                                1906</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 208.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: On June 23 I had the honor of leaving at
                            the State Department a memorandum respecting the leasing to the British
                            North Borneo Company of certain small islands off the coast of
                            Borneo.</p>
                        <p>I have now received a dispatch from His Majesty’s secretary of state for
                            foreign affairs, inquiring what progress has been made in the matter,
                            and accordingly I have the honor to ask you to be so good as to inform
                            me whether it has yet been found possible to come to any decision as to
                            the proposals set forth in the memorandum referred to above.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">H. M. Durand.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>